column168: Undeclared Hazmat was found during the loading process of our morning flight.  The hazmat had been part of a larger pallet of cases of water and other boxes. The pallet was Bypass Mail from the Post Office and had already traveled by truck to our facility. Bottle clearly has Class 3 Flammable Liquid on the side.

column168: As the Afternoon Car Inspector was inspecting cars in the Brewster yard, he noticed a strong odor coming from PROX 37117 at about 1710 hrs.  He came to my office, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for WLE and reported it.  I went to the yard with him to investigate, and found that his car was indeed leaking from the liquid valve on the A end.  I tried to tighten the valve to see if it was loose and it was. The leak stopped once I tightened the valve. I found that the valve plug was loose as were the other valve plugs. I tightened all valve plugs and released the car for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

I checked to see if the valve was loose and it was.  I tightened the valve and the leak stopped.  The plug was also loose as were the valve plugs on all the other valves.  I tightened all the valve plugs and released the car for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

In his first stop of the day for waste oil collection, the driver mistakenly engaged the pump of the truck in what he thought to be the “suction” setting; the pump was in fact the “blowing” setting. When the driver tried to detach and relocate the product hose, approximately one gallon of used motor oil was released to the asphalt parking lot; no soil or water ways were impacted. The spill was immediately contained by the driver and facility personnel wearing the correct personal protective equipment, The spill was remediated using absorbent pads and granular absorbent material. The waste material from the cleanup was properly containerized for later disposal. The spill was reported to Victor Fonkem of the Massachusetts DEP at 13:11 on 12/7/16; the tracking number is 3-33979.
column169: We discovered that the driver was unfamiliar with this particular tank unit, and that the label for the pump lever was partially obscured. The driver has received additional familiarization and training on the particular tank vehicle in question, and the label for the pump operating lever has been renewed.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A driver returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility after making a pickup of a shipment of hazardous waste.  He began unloading the totes with a pallet jack onto the dock and hit the valve on an adjacent tote--cracking it.  He immediately placed absorbent pads around the leaking valve and a response crew was summoned.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, they transferred the contents into a new tote.  The valve was replaced on the old tote and the absorbent pads were also placed into the new tote.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver was disciplined and instructed to be more careful when using a pallet jack.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was picked up and returned to the intermediate truck transfer facility.  The truck was not unloaded that night but was to be unloaded the next morning.  Upon opening the rear door, it was noticed that there was liquid on the floor, ceiling and sides of the inside of the box truck.  The cap of the tote was laying on the floor and was cracked.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and transferred the contents to another tote, along with the absorbent pads and cleaning compound used to clean the inside of the box truck and a small area of concrete beneath the truck.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The generator was notified to not overfill the totes and leave enough head space for expansion of the contents.  It was a warm evening and the tote cap burst off from the expansion of the contents.  The driver was also instructed not to accept totes that are overfilled.

column168: At 0449 hrs on 2/13/2016 when switching cars in the WLE Brewster Yard, the train crew noticed a petroleum odor around tank car GATX 214859.  The WLE yardmaster notified myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came to the yard to investigate and found vapors coming from the vacuum relief device. I removed seal #1383723 from the lid of the housing and I took the tamper proof cap off the device and tried to manually operate the valve in order to get it to re-seat but it would not.  I could not get it to stop leaking.  I made a report to Chemtrec who in turn contacted the shipper, Markwest.  They dispatched their Emergency Responder, SunPro.  They came out and with my help, took the faulty valve off the car.  When we took the valve off and looked at the rubber seal on the valve. I noticed that the rubber seal was swollen as if the rubber material was not compatible with the material in the car.  The rubber seal was not damaged, it was just swollen causing it to not seal properly.  Sunpro installed a new vacuum relief device and then bubble tested the car with Nitrogen.  The car passed a 30 pound test and then car was then released for service.  New seal # 1380517 was applied to the housing of the car.
column169: When devices are applied to the car, compatibility of gaskets needs to be checked.  Not sure this leak would have been noticed in the loading phase of the car.

column168: AT 2:15 ON 12-2-2016, A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY CREW WORKING IN THE KANSAS CITY, MO KNOCHE YARD REPORTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR. column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES. AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64212. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: When the yard crew was switching cars in Brewster yard, they noticed an odor coming from car TILX 302484.  They notified the yardmaster who called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I went to the yard to investigate and found that the vapor valve was partially open and the plug was less than hand tight.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped and then I tightened the valve plug.  The plugs in both the liquid valves were loose also but not leaking.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: When the WLE Brewster car inspector was inspecting cars on the inbound train in Brewster Yard, he noticed an odor coming from GATX 214859.  He contacted the yardmaster who called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came out to investigate and found that vapors were coming from the vacuum relief device.  I took the tamper proof top off of the valve and tried to operate it manually to see if I could get the valve to re seat.  It would not re seat after several tries.  I contacted Chemtrec who in turn contacted the shipper, Markwest.  Markwest called their Emergency Response Contractor Sunpro who came out and looked at the car.  They brought out a new vacuum relief device and installed it on the car.  They car was then bubble tested with 30lbs. of Nitrogen.  The car passed the leak test and then was released for service.
column169: I am not sure that this would have been found upon loading of the car.  I think under very little pressure, that the leak would not have been detected.  It is my opinion that the seal on the valve was not compatible with the product in the car causing the seal to swell and not seal properly.

column168: While loading a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility at the intermediate truck transfer facility, it was noticed that a small stream of liquid was on the trailer floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found that the bottom valve fitting was cracked.  A cam lock fitting had broken off and the ball valve was leaking.  The tote was unloaded and placed onto a containment pan.  The contents were transferred to a new tote and the material used to clean up the spill and the pan were also placed into the new tote.  The shipment was then loaded back onto the trailer without further incident.
column169: The driver should have noticed the broken cam lock fitting even though the tote was not leaking at the time.  The container also did not have DOT markings on it and should not have been picked up.  The generator was notified of the incident and is investigating.

column168: FedEx driver at delivery breaking down shrunk wrapped pallet of boxes. After removing 1 row of boxes he notified FedEx & consignee of 24 boxes that were wet. Each box had 2/1 liter plastic bottle inside. A box from row 2 & 4 each had 1  bottle inside that failed. FedEx contacted clean up company AAG Environmental. Prior to clean-up company's arrival the consignee removed the damaged freight and took those boxes inside delivery. Consignee also placed 24 wet boxes inside plastic bags and placed them back on FedEx truck. Consignee refused to give FedEx any details of the damaged freight and left the incident scene. When the clean up company arrived they removed the damaged freight from the FedEx truck for proper disposal.  The shipped was unavailable during the incident. It was discovered the boxes in the middle of the pallet were undeclared UN2031 Nitric Acid and UN3265. Two of the leaking boxes were the UN2031. Shipper has also failed to return our calls.
column169: Hazardous Materials training & communication could be improved at the shippers and the consignees level.

column168: AT 1847 HRS ON 12/2/106. IT WAS REPORTED THAT HAZMAT CAR SHQZ 50569 WAS LEAKING AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) KNOCHE RAIL WAY IN KANSAS CITY MO. THE KSC ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT ALONG WITH A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, RESPONDED TO THE YARD TO INVESTIGATE. THE SHQX 50569 WAS FOUND WITH BOTH THE A AND B LIQUID VALVES IN 1/8 TURN OPEN POSITION AND BOTH SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUGS LOOSE AND LEAKING AT A STEADY RATE. ALSO THE VAPOR VALVE WAS FOUND IN THE 1/8 TURN OPEN POSITION WITH SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG LOOSE AND LEAKING. THE CONDITION OCCURRED BECAUSE SHIPPER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THESE TANK CAR CLOSURES BEFORE OFFERING INTO TRANSPORTATION. THE ATMOSPHERE AROUND THE TANK CAR, GROUND LEVEL BREATHING ZONE AND ON TOP OF THE CAR BREATHING ZONE WAS FOUND TO BE ABSENT FLAMMABILITY PERCENTAGE AND REGISTERED ON 1-2 PPM VOATILE ORGANIC COMPOUND (VOC). ALL LOOSE CLOSURES WERE SECURED TOOL TIGHT AND THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION. FILE NOTE: ITEM 19 THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILLING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS "BULK" SHIPMENT AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTITY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASE (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (AKA PACKAGE CLOSURES ISSUES SUCH AS THIS) THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT CASE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSES OF RELEASE AND TO NON FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, LCS RAILWAY PO BOX 219335 KANSAS CITY MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: Driver was unable to deliver shipment because internal valve was frozen, driver brought load back to terminal for assistance. Shop placed trailer in steam bay, removed external valve, applied steam, internal valve was frozen open, product leaked out. Remote was broken but material still came out of trailer. Terminal personnel was able to attach external valve and stop release.      On 12/27/2016 the material was transferred from trailer 21854 to 21326.;  ;  On 12/28/2016 General Service Manager reported: the trailer is now clean and back inside the shop, we vacuum tested both valves- both pass. We then dis-assembled the internal valve to confirm there are no broken parts present. The only issue that we found is glycol inside the valve barrel- we are now replacing all the soft parts in the internal valve. During our entry we found no foreign objects inside the barrel or in the valve assembly. When we are done we will again confirm valve operation.    Mechanic error, inattention, carelessness. Removed external valve under load and allowed steaming of frozen internal valve and wet lines with external valve removed.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: This incident pertains to a release of battery acid that was shipped as UN2794 batteries, wet, filled with acid. There was (1) - 2100 pound battery that was damaged and released approximately a half liter of product. This battery fell to the ground during unloading operations and battery acid released from one of the caps. This release impacted a portion of the trailer and dock floor. XPO Logistics personnel conducted cleanup operations for this release. The battery was staged on site pending the shippers disposition.

A 330 gal poly tote of UN1993 was punctured on the base by a forklift during unloading. 1 qt of material released onto the trailer and dock floor. Hazmat contractors arrived onsite and transferred the product into a new tote for salvage.

It was reported that during loading 1-55 gallon metal drum of Methanol was impacted by a forklift. The impacted drum released all 55 gallons to the trailer floor and the parking area. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and to manage all waste generated.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Residue tank car, UTLX 902016, was discovered to be leaking in the Proviso Yard located in Northlake, IL. Upon inspection it was found that the (A) End liquid line valve was partially open with a less than tool tight plug. In addition, the vapor line valve was  partially open with a less than tool tight plug as well.   The valves were turned completely closed and both plugs were secured tool tight.
column169: Ensure proper securement of all valves and fittings prior to releasing into transportation. Refer to Pamphlet 34 for guidance and training.

column168: At 1115 ERTS was contacted by Curt Meixner of XPO Logistics - XYH to report a spill. It was reported that terminal personnel discovered (1) 55 Gallon Drum of UN1760 Contains Sodium Hydroxide Potassium Hydroxide to have a loose bung cap and appears to have released approximately 10 ounces to the top of the drum. This release was discovered inside of trailer #3153264. Terminal personnel requesting a contractor, ERTS dispatched Northridge Group to overpack the damaged drum.

column42: HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WITH NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT STRENGTH
column168: The load of Hydrofluoric acid on a shipping container, the container doors were opened at the customer and it was discovered that the wood bracing to hold one of the drums was pierced at the base by a nail. Small spill in the container only but the vapors from the spill came out when the doors were opened. A clean up crew is in route to the location for clean up of the spill.
column169: The shipper has been advised of the incident to discuss with the company when loading the container to be aware of how the bracing for the load is handled.

column168: On December 16, 2016, during unloading operations, terminal personnel discovered (2) 330-gallon poly totes containing UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid with loose caps. The caller stated that approximately 2-ounces released to the top of the totes during transit. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing absorbents pads and soda ash. The caps were tightened and secured.

There was no package failure..  Our driver began unloading the CTMV and saw a release from the consignee's unloading hose..  Our driver closed the internal and external valves to stop the release.. The consignee's hose is not part of the package..  The consignee's hose had two (2) pinholes in the middle of the hose..  It took no more than one (1) minute to close the valves and stop the product from releasing from the pinholes.. A good replacement hose was used to continue unloading the CTMV..     Our reference Event/Claim # 62819-1..

column168: On 12/05/2016 at 1319 North Broad St, Hillside, NJ, a Monty's Express trailer experienced a load shift causing (4) 55 gallon poly drums of UN1805 phosphoric acid solution to fall over.  The 4 drums released approximately 3 gallons of material through self venting bung caps.  The release impacted the trailer floor and approximately 2 ounces of material released to the asphalt parking lot. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  On 12/6/2016 an environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  The released material was neutralized with a soda ash solution and cleaned with granular absorbents.  The leaking drums were cleaned off and secured on the trailer floor.  All waste was removed and taken for disposal by the environmental contractor.  The secured drums were left on the trailer for Monty's Express to manage.

On 12/06/2016 hazmat inspector Christopher Kuenzi conducted an inspection of railcars at Peninsula Terminal's interchange tracks. While on top of railcar GATX 1765 he noticed a hissing noise coming from underneath the doghouse. Under further inspection he found the vent valve to be bad ordered. I notified GATX Company and they ordered the correct part to replace. This was also forwarded to the transload company on site, MP Environmental, as this car was shipped to them from Ash Grove Cement. This car was an empty residue last contained.     There was no actual spill (only a vent) although question #19 on this report would not let me enter 0, so I used 1 cup as an answer so that the report would allow me to continue.

CN mechanical department employee reported a vapor cloud coming from the top of tank car UTLX 130530 (R / HYDROCHLORIC ACID, UN1789, Class 8, PG II) during a train inspection at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA.  All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the that the fill hole cover bolt was not properly secured and tool tight.  The fill hole cover was secured by shipper seal # 0161442.  The seal was removed and the fill hole cover was secured by tightening the fill hole cover bolt.  The rail-car was deconned and released for further movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On 12/20/2016, at the R&L Carriers terminal in Wilmington, OH, a 55 gallon poly drum of UN1719 Proxel GXL arrived damaged and leaking in a trailer.  The drum had been punctured by a protruding piece of metal from the trailer wall.  The damaged drum released approximately 3 gallons of material to the trailer floor. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  The release was neutralized with a citric acid solution and cleaned with granular absorbents.  All impacted absorbents were containerized into a 15 gallon poly drum and taken offsite for disposal.  The damaged drum was over packed into a 95 gallon poly drum. The over pack was labeled with all applicable shipping information and staged on site for R&L personnel to manage.

On 12/21/2016, a 5 gallon poly jerrycan of UN3105 Trigonox 131 arrived with fork lift damage at the R&L Carriers Terminal in Wilmington, OH.  The damaged jerrycan released approximately 5 gallons of material to the trailer floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  The released material was cleaned with granular absorbents.  All impacted absorbents and the damaged jerrycan were containerized into (2) 20 gallon poly drums.  The drums of waste were staged onsite for R&L personnel to manage.

column168: On 12/27/2016 at the R&L Carriers terminal in Phoenix, AZ, a 2400 lbs UN2794 battery broke through the pallet on which it was staged.  The battery fell over causing approximately 3 gallons of battery acid to release through the battery caps. The release impacted the dock floor and no soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release and secure the battery.  The release was neutralized with a sodium bicarbonate solution and cleaned with granular absorbents.  The battery was wiped clean and the caps closed and secured.  The battery was left on site for R&L personnel to manage.  All waste was taken offsite for disposal.

CS Freightways was hired to transport chemicals contained in totes, order 4S102090, from 100 West Sterrett Road in Waxahachie, Texas, to 2310 Wolfcamp Circle in Midland, Texas.  CS Freightways’ truck 01 was travelling west on interstate 20 and moved from the right lane to the left lane to allow traffic from an on ramp to enter I20.  The driver of a four door sedan put on her left blinker in an to attempt to change lanes from the right lane to the left lane and turned into truck 01 directly in front of the back axles of the truck.  The sedan went up underneath truck 01, and the truck and sedan together drifted off the road to the right and came to a stop on the right side of I20 near mile marker 413 in the city of Hudson Oaks, Texas.  The impact of the collision caused some of the totes to rupture and thus spill chemicals.  The driver of truck 01, the driver of the sedan, and the passenger in the sedan were all transported to the hospital via ambulance, checked out/observed, and released.
column169: CS Freightways is dedicated to making safety a top priority.  We will continue best practices, such as remaining in the right lane unless passing is required for on ramp access or slower moving traffic, driving with lights on, and checking all mirrors regularly.  In future safety meetings, we will discuss methods to be more aware of inattentive drivers and our position on the road.  We will also leave a larger escape route in an effort to increase driver response time.

column42: METHANE, COMPRESSED OR NATURAL GAS, COMPRESSED (WITH HIGH METHANE CONTENT)
column168: As part of the commissioning of a newly acquired Hexagon Lincoln Titan XL Trailer, Xpress Natural Gas was loading with Compressed Natural Gas. The Loading Operator started to hear "popping" noises, smelled mercaptain coming from the inside of the trailer. Emergency Stop Devices (ESD's) were activated shutting down the delivery of Compressed Natural Gas to the trailers. The Eliot Fire Department was summoned per protocol. Xpress Natural Gas Engineer and Safety Director arrived on scene. After investigation of the trailer, it was discovered that compressed natural gas had somehow seeped between the inner composite cylinder and the liner. Since the gas was under pressure, the "popping" noises were being made as the trapped gas evacuated through the liner, dissipating into the atmosphere. The cylinder was isolated and vented slowly to fully empty. The trailer was transported back to Hexagon Manufacturer for cylinder removal, replacement and further testing.
column169: The subject Titan XL Trailer was returned to Hexagon Lincoln for further evaluating and testing.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: The tank was out of gas upon arrival,it passed a Ferrellmeter so the driver proceeded to fill the tank. While filling the tank the driver noticed the ground frosting, so he did a ESO and called his operations manager for further instructions. The driver waited on site till product was no longer coming up from the ground and frosting dissipated. From that point he probed the ground in over 40 places morning and night for the next few days till the readings were below flammable limits. We then dug the tank out of the ground. The tank had been sitting empty from 2012 to present.The tank had several holes eaten through it. No injuries, No other property damage.

column168: On December 27, 2016, at 14:00 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Avon Terminal, in Avon, Indiana reported that a strong odor was detected around SUJX 299056, a loaded tank car of UN2448,Sulfur. The shipper, Oxbow Sulfur (C/O Canal Terminal), was notified via Chemtrec, report #2016-12-27-00141. Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal. Sunpro found that there was only a release of vapor from an improperly secured man-way and verified with an H2S meter. All six man-way securement bolts were found less than tool tight. There was a small amount of residual sulfur suspected to have no been released from this incident.The shipper representative, KELLE BROWN 281-907-9275, was notified of the situation found.     NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code:212

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE TRANSPORT STATED HE MADE CONNECTIONS TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT THE CONVENINCE STORE AS USUAL. THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE OVERFILED THE TANK, AND AS SOON AS HE OBSERVED FUEL COMING OUT OF THE FILL SPOUT HE CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE TRANSPORT. THE DRIVER THEN STATED THAT WITH THE HOSE STILL CONNECTED TO THE FILL SPOUT, THE REMAINING FUEL IN THE HOSE DRAINED INTO THE TANK. THE DRIVE STATED THAT HE BELIEVED IT WAS A PRESSURE RELIEF ISSUE, BUT WAS UNSURE AND COULD NOT IDENTIFY A DIRECT CAUSE. THE DRIVER THEN CONTACTED DISPATCH AND INFORMED THEM OF THE RELEASE. DISPATCH CONTACTED LOCAL AUTHORITIES AS WELL AS HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FOR CLEANUP
column169: REMEDIAL TRAINING, AS WELL AS A CHECKLIST TO INSURE THAT UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS ARE PROPERLY VENTED.WHEN ON SITE, REQUEST FACILITY TANK CHARTS TO IDENTIFY SIZE OF TANKS AND COMPARE TO AMOUNT OF FUEL TO BE OFF LOADED.

column168: On 12/12/2016 at approximately 1745 hours it was reported that while inspecting cars in the Barstow trainyard a strong smell of fuel/alcohol was discovered in the immediate area of tank car TILX 194841 a load of Alcohols N.O.S. placarded UN1987.  Local BNSF hazmat responders investigated and found the smell coming from the manway lid.  The responders opened the manway and discovered a hardened and deteriorated manway nozzle gasket which was unable to provide a vapor and liquid proof seal.  The gasket was replaced with a new one, and all other closures and securement devices were inspected for compliance with no additional exceptions.  There were no casualties and no environmental impact requiring remediation.  Upon completion of the inspection and repair, the car was released for movement to destination for unloading.  Quantity of release of 1 cubic foot is an estimate based on reports from response personnel.
column169: All cars must have a complete inspection of gaskets and closures prior to departure.  Retraining and random quality assurance audits are recommended to ensure adequate pre-trip inspections are performed to ensure a release does not occur in transportation per federal requirements.

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discover a pail that had been crushed by a pallet that had slid into it during transit. As a result the bottom of the pail was crushed contributing to the unintentional release.Spilled material was neutralized and put into a recovery container as was the damaged pail.
column169: Dunnage in between shipments and better blocking and bracing could have prevented this unintentional release from occurring.

column168: TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLLOVER DUE TO THE INCORRECT LANE POSITION WITH COMPLETING A LEFT TURN. ONCE WE WERE CONTACTED BY THE DRIVER, THE COMPANY CALLED OUR INSURANCE CARRIER AND THEY CONTACTED A SPILL TEAM. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A LIQUID PIPE ON TOP OF THE TANKER THAT WAS CRACKED DURING THE ROLLOVER.     THE SPILL TEAM ARRIVED AND STARTED CLEANUP OPERATIONS IMMEDIATELY. COAL CITY COB SENT ANOTHER VACUUM TRUCK TO REMOVE THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM OUR TRAILER, THE CLEAN UP CREW REMOVED THE SPILL LIQUID FROM THE ROAD SURFACE AND THE STORM DRAIN AND PLACED THE PRODUCT INTO SPILL CONTAINMENT CONTAINERS.     ONCE THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED, THE TRANSFER PRODUCT WAS TAKEN TO THE RECEIVER TM AT 2525 INDEPENDENCE PARKWAY SOUTH DEER PARK TX 77536.     THE REMAINING CLEANUP MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED BY UNIVAR. WE ARE WORKING WITH APPROVAL THROUGH UNIVAR AND THE DISPOSAL WILL BE THROUGH US ECOLOGY.
column169: WE IMMEDIATELY ISSUED A STATEMENT TO ALL OF OUR DRIVERS REGARDING THE USE OF THE CORRECT TURNING LANE. THIS WAS FOLLOWED BY VIDEO TRAINING THAT INCLUDES RIGHT TURNS, LEFT TURNS AND INTERSECTIONS AND SPEED AND SPACE MANAGEMENT.

column168: On 12/13 at 2050 EST, Greg Stoufer with WG Saterlee & Sons called ERTS regarding a 500+ gallon release of diesel from a 406 tanker in Folsom, WV on route 20 near MM1. The spill was the result of a rollover causing the tanker to spill. Approximately 800 gallons from the 6000 gallons within the unit released, impacting the roadway, local soils and a creek.     Free product was taken up with vacuum trucks.  The impacted soils have been excavated.  The entire site has been remediated, as of this date.
column169: Better driver training may have prevented the release.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: At 1155 a.m. the driver was loading the roll-off container onto the trailer for transport. While securing the container to the chassis, the driver noticed a small puddle on the ground and some product dribbling from the container door. The driver accessed a ladder and inspected the cargo where he found the product had phase shifted during transport causing free liquid to be liberated. The material which had leaked onto the ground was removed along with an additional 5 inches of earth and gravel. The recovered material was placed in the original container along with additional absorbent material to solidify the free liquid and shipped for disposal. The door of the container was adjusted and tightened to prevent further incident. The container was then delivered to its destination for disposal.
column169: Discussions have been held with all parties involved with regard to proper container selection and preparation to ensure the containers used are appropriate for the material being shipped.

column168: On December 16, 2016 at approximately 0830 PT in the BNSF trainyard in Everett, WA tank car GATX 79641 was found to have wetness around the bottom outlet cap and a slight drip by yard personnel.  BNSF hazmat responder arrived and investigated and found a placarded tank car UN1993 with billing reflecting a STCC code of 4912259 (Flammable Liquids N.O.S. Nonene).  Found an active drip from the bottom outlet cap.  The cap/plug assembly was on too tight for him to remove and further evaluate so a plastic bag was taped around the nozzle assembly while additional resources arrived to assist.  With lubrication and a 48" pipe wrench the bottom outlet plug was removed as well as the cap.  No additional liquid was present in the cap, and investigation of the ball valve revealed no defects or product bypass.  New outlet cap gasket was applied and plug assembly was restored and car was released for departure.  No injuries, waterways, or environmental damage.
column169: Review loading/unloading process with rack personnel to ensure no product is left in nozzles or caps prior to departure.

column168: Approximately 4 oz. of UN3378 "Regenox Part A" released from a 40 lb. plastic bag that appeared to be punctured by a forklift. The release occurred on the dock and impacted the concrete dock floor. An environmental contractor responded and performed cleanup operations. The damaged bag and sweepings were over packed into a 30 gallon poly salvage drum.

Approximately 2 cups of UN1198 Formaldehyde Solution released from a 275 gallon poly tote due to a loose cap. The release impacted the body of the tote and leaked to the concrete dock floor below. An environmental contractor responded, cleaned the release and tightened the loose cap. The tote was mechanically agitated and did not leak following corrective action. All waste debris was containerized for proper disposal.

column168: On 12/20/16, the Phoenix IBU received a report of SNLU 133909 leaking by the assigned driver. The unit was moved to the containment pit. Schneider Cargo Claims was notified via phone and they enlisted ERTS for dispatch of contractor Kary Environmental. The contractor advised the leaking product was identified as Zep Industrial Purple Cleaner and Degreaser (corrosive); approximately 4 gallons were released. This was a palatalized mixed freight load secured with two TyGard strips at the rear. The cause was due to two screws from the aluminum exterior box for shipping paperwork extending past the nose panel on the interior and puncturing the pail. The contractor provided the necessary cleanup and the unit was released.
column169: Shipper advised of condition leading to release (protruding screws).  Shipper should take action to prevent objects from impacting shipments of hazardous materials in transportation.

column168: When the Rook Yard Crew was switching, they noticed an odor coming from TAEX 2388 at 0350 hrs..  When they investigated, they noticed a drip coming from the bottom outlet valve.  They called the WEL Brewster Dispatcher who in turn called myself, John Vergis, WLE Environmental Officer.  I called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to go look at the car.  When they arrived, they saw that the gasket between the internal ball valve portion of the bottom outlet valve, and the valve nozzle was leaking. This is a bolted, flanged connection.  They tried to tighten the mounting bolts but they were already tight.  The gasket was defective.  They installed a Haz hammock under the car to contain any drips until further action was taken. I contacted Chemtrec who in turn put the shipper, Markwest in touch with me.  We determined that the car needed to be transloaded and that the gasket would need to be replaced.  The car was transloaded on 1-3-2017.  Repairs were completed on the car on 1-17-2017 and the car was released for transportation.  Both the transload and repair operations were performed by Sunpro out of Canton, OH.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the staging operation, it was discovered that approximately 1 pint of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the liner. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.   IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation.  Both shipper and transporter agree that moving forward the material will be shipped in containers rated for liquid.

column168: A BNSF yard employee detected a "bleach-like" odor as a chlorine tank car passed by in the yard. No visible vapor or liquid release was noted, just an odor.  A BNSF HazMat advisor was on scene and noted no odor from a distance, nor any visible liquid or vapor leak after zooming in with a yard camera. The contractor arrived on the site and performed some initial air monitoring of the site, noting 0.7ppm of chlorine at a distance of 150 feet and downwind.  The contractor donned PPE and climbed the car, detecting 0.9ppm just outside the protective housing.    The protective housing lid was opened and after utilizing ammonia vapor for detection, found the "A" end liquid line valve partially open with a less-than-tool-tight plug. The valve was closed and the plug was removed, taped, and tool tightened. The other three valves were checked for closure and the three other plugs were removed, taped, and tool tightened.    Air monitoring of the housing immediately after and about 20 minutes later provided with negative readings of any presence of chlorine.     The employee that was exposed did go to the emergency room following the working shift and was released with no treatment or admittance necessary.
column169: Shipper MUST ensure that the valves are closed properly and the plugs are taped and tool tightened to ensure that no leakage of product occurs. This is a TIH/PIH material that could have severe consequences to human health if released from the designed packaging. Shipper must take greater care and responsibility with such a material.

column168: ON FRIDAY, DEC 9, 2016 THE OPERATOR (DRIVER) OF TANK TRUCK FOR PENN TANK LINES, INC. WHILE MAKING DELIVERY OF REGULAR UNLEADED (E 10/87 OCTANE) ATTEMPTED TO MOVE UNIT WHILE THE DELIVERY HOSE WAS CONNECTED AT THE FILL FOR THE UST AND TO THE TRAILER. THE DELIVERY HOSE PULLED FOR TRAILER RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY REPOSTED THE RELEASE TO HIS TERMINAL. HEPACO (EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROVIDER) FOR THE CARRIER WAS CALLED FOR RESPONSE & ASSISTANCE. ON ARRIVAL AT  SITE HEPACO INTERMEDIATELY BEGIN TO PROVIDE SPILL RESPONSE. LATER THAT EVENING ATTENDANT/CLERKS BEGIN TO OBSERVE THE STRONG ODER OF GASOLINE FUMES IN THE BUILDING. THE STATION WAS CLOSED AND EMPLOYEES SENT HOME. ON NOTIFICATION BY SPEEDWAY, SATURDAY MORNING, DEC 10TH HEPACO RETURNED TO THE SITE AND RECORDED READINGS ABOVE THE PERMITTED LEVEL FOR BENZINE EXPOSURE AS ESTABLISHED BY OSHA. EMPLOYEES WERE SENT HOME AND THE BUILDING CLOSED. FOLLOWING INSPECTION OF THE BUILDING HEPACO IDENTIFIED THE ENTRY POINTS OF THE FUMES. VAPORS AND SEALED THESE ENTRY POINTS. AFTER REMOVING SOIL, PEA GRAVEL, ASPHALT AND LATER A SECTION OF CEMENT, AN EXHAUST FAN WAS PLACED AT THE REAR OF THE BUILDING TO PULL ANY VAPORS OUT FROM UNDER THE BUILDING. LEVELS WERE BROUGHT DOWN TO A SAFE LEVEL AS DEFINED BY REGULATION. LATER VENTILATION CONSISTING OF A RADON FAN WAS INSTALLED TO HELP MAINTAIN LOW LEVELS OF EXPOSURES AS REQUIRED. THE AREA IMPACTED BY THE SPILL INCLUDED THE FOLLOWING CEMENT SPILL PAD, ASPHALT AND SOIL/STONE ON THE REAR OF THE BUILDING & ADJACENT PROPERTY WHICH IS ASPHALT AND SHOWN AS AN ALLEY ON SITE PLANS  PROVIDED BY SPEEDWAY. AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL THERE WAS NO KNOWN WATER WAY OR SEWERS IMPACTED BY THIS SPILL. TAYLOR GEO WAS RETAINED BY THE CARRIER (TANK TRUCK) TO OVERSEE & DIRECT REMEDIATION EFFORTS. ALSO ON SITE WAS ACT WHO SERVES AS SPEEDWAY ENVIRONMENTAL REPRESENTATIVE. ALL MATERIAL THAT HAS BEEN REMOVED AT THIS TIME HAS BEEN BARRELED FOR DISPOSAL AS REQUIRED BY FEDERAL & STATE REGULATIONS. CURRENTLY TAYLOR GEO SERVICE IS CREATING A PLAN FOR FURTHER REMEDIATION FOR ANY AREAS IMPACTED BY THE SPILL INCLUDING THE ELIMINATION OF VAPOR/ FUMES IN THE BUILDING.

column168: AN EAST PENN TRUCK DRIVER WAS DRIVING ON HIGHWAY 40 NEAR UNION CROSS AT EXIT 201 WHEN ANOTHER VEHICLE CUT IN FRONT OF HIM. THE VEHICLE BRAKED AND LOST CONTROL OF THEIR CAR. THE EAST PENN TRUCK DRIVER TRIED TO AVOID HITTING THE OTHER VEHICLE BY TURNING TO THE LEFT. IN DOING SO HE ENDED UP HITTING THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE OTHER VEHICLE AND OVERTURNING HIS TRUCK. THE TRUCK SLID INTO THE MEDIAN AND THE CARGO SPILLED OUT ONTO THE HIGHWAY.     THE KERNERSVILLE HAZ MAT TEAM WAS ON SITE WHEN SWS, THE CONTRACTED CLEAN UP SERVICE COMPANY, ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. SWS PUT DOWN QUICKKLEEN ON THE AREAS WHERE ACID SPILLED OUT OF THE BATTERIES. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PUT DOWN OIL DRY ON THE SPILLED DIESEL FLUID.     A TOW SERVICE WAS ALSO CONTACTED. WHEN THEY ARRIVED THEY WERE ABLE TO UPRIGHT THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. A ROLL OFF CONTAINER WAS BROUGHT ON SITE TO PUT ALL THE BROKEN BATTERIES INTO TO GET THEM OFF THE ROAD QUICKLY SO THEY COULD RE-OPEN THE ROAD. THE CONTRACTOR TOOK THE ROLL OFF BACK TO HIS SHIP TO PUT THE BATTERIES INTO OVER PACK DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THE OVER PACK DRUM WERE DELIVERED BACK TO EAST PENN FOR DISPOSAL AT ITS OWN SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER.     ANY GOOD BATTERIES WERE PICKED UP BY EAST PENN AND RE-PALATALIZED AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE EAST PENN DISTRIBUTION CENTER IN WINSTON SALEM.     THE DRUMMED WASTE OF CLEAN UP MATERIAL FROM THE DIESEL FUEL AND SULFURIC ACID WAS SENT TO CLEAN HARBORS FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: LAW ENFORCEMENT DEEMED THIS A NON-PREVENTABLE INCIDENT AND CITED THE OTHER DRIVER FOR RECKLESS DRIVING. EAST PENN WILL CONTINUE WITH DEFENSIVE DRIVE TRAINING AS WELL AS REGULATORY COMPLIANCE TRAINING. THERE WAS NO ACTION THE TRUCK DRIVER COULD HAVE TAKEN TO AVOID THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON DECEMBER 14, 2016, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:15 P.M. CST, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY U.S. LOGISTICS (USL) WAS TRAVELING AT THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION WHEN THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A CARGO LEAK. AS A RESULT OF THE LEAK, APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIETHYLAMINE WAS RELEASED TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON LEAKED OUT FROM THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE ASPHALT SURFACE BELOW. , MEG PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. CREWS OBSERVED A SMALL AREA OF IMPACTED ASPHALT UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER. CREWS DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENTS TO THE DIETHYLAMINE-IMPACTED ASPHALT AND SWEPT THEM IN WITH HAND TOOLS. AMEG PERSONNEL DONNED LEVEL C PPE BEFORE OPENING THE TRAILER AND ENTERING. CREWS OBSERVED APPROXIMATELY 5 - 10 GALLONS OF DIETHYLAMINE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. MEG DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENT TO THE IMPACTED TRAILER AND ALONG THE EXIT ROUTES TO ESTABLISH CONTAINMENT. THE CARGO WAS CONTAINED IN PALLETS OF 55-GALLON STEEL DRUMS. MEG IDENTIFIED ONE (1) LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUM OF DIETHYLAMINE AND UTILIZED ABSORBENTS TO STOP THE LEAK. LIGHT SOURCES IN THE AREA WERE LIMITED AND LIGHT PLANTS WERE RULED OUT FOR BEING AN IGNITION SOURCE. CREWS SCHEDULED TO RETURN THE FOLLOWING DAY TO UTILIZE A FORK-LIFT TO UNLOAD THE CARGO IN THE DAYLIGHT SO THE TRAILER COULD BE UNLOADED AND FULLY REMEDIATED. ALL SPENT ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. CREWS SECURED THE SCENE AND DEMOBILIZED.     ON DECEMBER 15, 2016, MEG CREWS RETURNED TO THE SITE TO PERFORM THE FINAL REMEDIATION. THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS MOVED TO A LOADING DOCK AND MEG DONNED PROPER PPE BEFORE UTILIZING A FORK LIFT AND PALLET JACK TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER AND PLACE THE PALLETS ON POLY SHEETING. AN ADDITIONAL 55-GALLON DRUM DIETHYLAMINE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING. BOTH LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS. SPENT ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO TWO (2) 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. IMPACTED WOODEN PALLETS WERE CUT UP AND PLACED IN DRUMS WITH THE SPENT ABSORBENTS. A VAPOR SUPPRESSANT WAS APPLIED TO INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE DOORS LEFT OPEN FOR IT TO AIR OUT. CREWS SECURED THE SCENE AND DEMOBILIZED.

column168: AT APPROX 2300 ON DEC 14, 2016 A LOADER ON A FORKLIFT PUNCTURED AN IBC WITH THE BLADES OF A FORKLIFT THAT WERE PROTRUDING PAST THE FREIGHT HE WAS MOVING ON THE DOCK. APPROX 300 GALS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID SPILLED. 911 WAS CALLED AND THE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED. FIRE/PD ORDERED SHELTER IN PLACED FOR A 1/4 BLOCK RADIUS AND CLOSED TWO SCHOOLS PAST THE RADIUS AS A PRECAUTION. ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW CLEANED UP THE SPILL, AN INDUSTRIAL HYGIENIST VERIFIED THE CLEANUP AND THE SAN JOAQUIN OFFICE OF ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW CLEANED UP THE SPILL, AN INDUSTRIAL HYGIENIST VERIFIED THE CLEANUP AND THE SAN JOAQUIN OFFICE OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH WAS NOTIFIED.
column169: THE LOADER RECEIVED CORRECTIVE ACTION. RETRAINING WAS PERFORMED (COMPANY WIDE)AS WELL AS AN AFTER ACTION MEETING AND FOLLOW UP. THE COMPANY HAS DECIDED NOT TO HAUL LIQUID HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN GREATER QUANTITY THAN 55 GALS, ALSO NO LONGER CARRY TABLE 1 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE MCS 150 WILL BE UPDATED TO REFLECT THIS SHORTLY. THE PRESIDENT AND THE SAFETY DIRECTOR VISITED LOCAL BUSINESSES WITHIN THE AFFECTED AREA TO ANSWER QUESTIONS AND BE OF ANY HELP TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC.

column168: OUR DRIVER WESTBOUND ON DULLES TOLL RD. (RT 267) AT EXIT 9B WHEN HE STARTED SLIDING DOWN THE RAMP AND STRUCK THE GUARD RAIL SEPARATING THE HIGHWAY AND RAMP. UPON IMPACT IT CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BREAK-OFF AT THE 5TH WHEEL RELEASING THE TRAILER WHICH ROLLED OVER BELLY UP. ONE COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER WAS BREACHED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE ONTO THE ROADWAY.
column169: WEATHER WAS DEFINITELY A MAJOR FACTOR IN THIS ACCIDENT. DRIVER WAS GOING 30 MPH WHEN THE UNIT HIT A PATCH OF BLACK ICE CAUSING IT TO SKID INTO THE GUARD RAIL, JACK-KNIFE AND OVERTURN. THERE WERE NUMEROUS ACCIDENTS IN THE AREA DUE TO THE ICE. WITH NO WARNING OF HAZARD, I DONT KNOW IF THE DRIVER COULD HAVE DONE ANYTHING TO PREVENT IT.

column168: THE DRIVER EXITED 120 ONTO 22ND STREET NORTH AT TOO HIGH A RATE OF SPEED. THE MOMENTUM FROM SURGE EFFECT OF THE FUEL SHIFTING IN THE CARGO TANK CAUSED THE TRUCK TO ROLL OVER ONTO ITS DRIVER SIDE, RUPTURING THE OUTER SHELL OF THE TANKS FRONT COMPARTMENT, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.
column169: ENHANCED TRAINING OF DRIVERS REGARDING PROPER TRAVELING SPEEDS WHEN NEGOTIATING TURNS/CURVES.

column168: THE DRIVER HOOKED UP THE HOSE TO THE VALVE ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRUCK AND THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE TO THE CUSTOMERS ABOVE GROUND TANK WHERE PRODUCT WAS TO BE DELIVERED. AFTER PUMPING FOR 10-15 MINUTES, THE END OF THE HOSE THAT WAS ATTACHED TO THE TRUCK CAME LOOSE OF THE TRUCK AND PRODUCT BEGAN SPILLING ON THE GROUND. UPON NOTICING THIS, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY HIT THE SHUT OFF ON THE TRUCK TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY BEGAN SPILL PROCEDURES. HE CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER, WHOSE PERSONNEL BEGAN TO HELP WITH SPILL CONTAINMENT. HE ALSO CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO SENT THE CARRIERS SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO THE CUSTOMER LOCATION. THE RESPONSE TEAM LEADER ALSO CONTACTED THE CARRIERS OUTSIDE THIRD PARTY SPILL RESPONDER. UPON ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, THE CARRIER'S RESPONSE TEAM LEADER MADE THE DETERMINATION THAT THE THIRD PARTY SPILL RESPONDER WAS NOT NEEDED AND HE CALLED THEM TO CANCEL THEIR RESPONSE. THE RESPONSE TEAM COMPLETED THE CLEAN-UP TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE CUSTOMER. NO PRODUCT LEFT THE CUSTOMERS PROPERTY. ALL RECOVERED PRODUCT AND USED CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF WITH APOGEE ENVIRONMENTAL, LLC.
column169: CARRIER REPRESENTATIVES NOTIFIED ALL DRIVERS THAT SAFETY STRAPS ARE REQUIRED ON ALL CAM LOCKS AND REINFORCED TO ALL DRIVERS THAT CLOSER ATTENTION NEEDS TO BE PAID TO ALL LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES INCLUDING DISTANCE FROM AND VISUAL AWARENESS OF THE LOADING OR UNLOADING PROCESS.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Tractor Trailer Southbound on I-95 overturned and caused the load of batteries to shift and become damaged.  As a result of the accident some of the batteries began leaking acid into the back of the truck and onto the ground under the truck.  The batteries were loaded on 14 wooden pallets in the trailer and when the load shifted the batteries became dislodged from the pallets.    ACE Environmental was called to the scene to handle the clean up.  Upon arrival the area was boomed off to contain the spilled diesel fuel and battery acid.  The trailer was transported to a MD DOT facility along I-95 where containment was set up under the damaged trailer to capture the leaking fluids. The batteries were separated into 2 categories damaged and undamaged.  The undamaged batteries were placed on pallets and shrink wrapped for later delivery.  The damaged batteries and absorbent materials were placed in drums for disposal.  A total of 16 drums of waste was generated.      The impacted soils were excavated and back filled on December 13, 2016. The area pressure washed.  A total of 6 tons of material and 212 gallons of wash water were collected and sent for disposal.
column169: This loss was from an auto accident.

column168: A CARGO TANK CONTAINING ETHANOL OVERTURNED THE REAR OF TWO TRAILERS WHILE MAKING A LEFT TURN UNDER THE INTERSTATE, WHICH CREATED A SMALL LEAK IN THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE CARGO TANK. THE LEAK CONTINUED FOR NEARLY FOUR HOURS UNTIL ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED ONTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.
column169: DRIVER MUST CONTROL SPEED OF VEHICLE IN ALL ADVERSE CONDITIONS WHICH INCLUDES CORNERING AND WEATHER RELATED ISSUES.

column168: FUEL WAS DELIVERED FROM CTMV INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. THE STORAGE TANK HAD NO GAUGE. THE CUSTOMER SAID THERE WAS PLENTY OF ROOM FOR THE FUEL TO FIT. IT DID NOT FIT, AND THE TANK WAS OVERFILLED, RESULTING IN THE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL FROM THE TANK VENT TO THE SNOW AND GRAVEL ON ONE SIDE OF THE TANK. THE CUSTOMER AND REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE LOCAL CO-OP THAT SOLD THE PRODUCT USED SORBENTS AND REMOVED CONTAMINATED SNOW AND GRAVEL. THESE WERE THEN PACKAGED FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: STORAGE TANK SHOULD HAVE A GAUGE TO SHOW THE HEIGHT OF THE CONTENTS.    STORAGE TANKS COULD BE PUT INTO CONTAINMENT, ALTHOUGH IN THIS INSTANCE, I BELIEVE THAT WOULD HAVE MADE CLEANUP MOREDIFFICULT AND WOULD NOT HAVE PREVENTED ANY OF THE LOSS. THE FROZEN GROUND SERVED A SIMILAR PURPOSE

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON ROUTE 1 & 9 FROM THE ROUTE 278 WESTBOUND RAMP. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER A VEHICLE CUT HIM OFF IN AN ATTEMPT TO GET AROUND THE TRUCK, CAUSING THE DRIVER TO SUDDENLY BRAKE, CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK THEN IMPACTED THE CEMENT BARRIER, AND FLIPPED OVER THE BARRIER LANDING ON THE DRIVER’S SIDE OF THE TRUCK IN THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF ROUTE 1 & 9. AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT THE MANHOLE COVERS GOT DAMAGED AND APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OUT OF THE 1900 GALLONS THAT WERE ON THE TRUCK SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER WANTING TO GET AWAY FROM THE TRUCK AND POTENTIAL DANGER SELF-EVACUATED AS WELL AS HELPING HIS PASSENGER GET OUT OF THE VEHICLE, AS A RESULT THEIR PHONES WERE LEFT ON THE TRUCK AND WERE NOT NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT FOR SEVERAL HOURS. UNION COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE LINDEN FD & EMS.
column169: A SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD TO DISCUSS THE ACCIDENT, THE DOT CARGO ROLLOVER PREVENTION VIDEO WAS SHOWN TO ALL DRIVER’S AND EXPLAINED WITH EXAMPLES OF ACCIDENT. A DISCUSSION OF THE DANGERS OF SPEEDING AND SUDDEN STOPPING ESPECIALLY AROUND CURVES AND ON AND OFF RAMPS WAS HELD WITH ALL DRIVERS.

column168: THE DRIVER BECAME DISTRACTED AND DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. HE TRIED TO CORRECT IT BUT WAS UNABLE. THE TRUCK & TRAILER ROLLED ONTO IT’S SIDE. TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED ON THE TOP REAR RIGHT SIDE WHICH IS WHERE THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS FIRED DUE TO THE INCIDENT. WE CONSTANTLY REMIND OUR DRIVERS TO PAY ATTENTION AND DRIVE SAFELY. ADDITIONAL TRAINING AND REMINDERS ABOUT SAFE DRIVING HAPPEN THROUGHOUT THE YEAR.

column17: AAA Oil, Inc. dba California Fuels
column25: AAA Oil, Inc. dba: California Fuels & Lubricants
column168: Driver was completing the end of his shift and returning to company's storage yard. at approximately 0315, the driver fell asleep and it appears the trailer went off to the side of the road.  This woke the driver and over corrected causing the trailer to land on its side.      The accident happened in a remote are of the state, and there were no injuries or property damage.    Driver refused a drug screening and was terminated about a week after the accident.
column169: In light of this event, our company has taken steps to prevent such accident to reoccur.  We've updated our monthly training program to include subjects like: Routine Driving, Fatigue,  and Tanker Roll Overs.   We've also created a black-out period between 12:00am - 3:00am.  We do not schedule any future deliveries during this period to avoid such accidents.      We hope with the additional training and eliminating the graveyard shift, will help prevent any future accidents.
column198: AAA Oil, Inc. dba: California Fuels & Lubricants

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ARRIVED AT FACILITY TO DELIVER 1503 GALLONS OF REGULAR NO LEAD GASOLINE, FACILITY PERSONNEL ADVISED THAT TANK WOULD HOLD THE 1503 GALLONS. THE TANK WAS AN ABOVE GROUND TANK WITH A CLOCK GAUGE FOR INVENTORY PURPOSES. DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO STICK TANK FOR VOLUME. THE FUEL HAD TO BE PUMPED FROM TRAILER INTO ABOVE GROUND TANK. THIS IS A NORMAL PROCEDURE. DRIVER NOTICED THAT GAUGE HAD STOPPED AND HE WENT TO SHUT OFF VALVE, AS HE DID SO, PRODUCT STARTED SPRAYING OUT TOP OF TANK. VALUE WAS SHUT OFF AND PRODUCT STOPPED SPILLING.  CLEAN UP CREW WAS CALLED AND “BIOMATRIX” WAS USED TO ABSORB THE GASOLINE. IMPACTED GRAVEL ABSORBENT WAS REMOVED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: FACILITY SHOULD MANUALLY DO INVENTORY TO RECONCILE ACTUAL INVENTORY WITH GAUGE.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AND WAS OPENED AND INSPECTED. IT WAS THEN DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE THREE INNER 14 OUNCES METAL CONTAINERS HAD FAILED AROUND THE CLOSURE AREA AND HAD SPILLED. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND ANGELIQUE MULDROW OF THE LAX/ FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AT 15:00 (CDT) OF THE INCIDENT, AND SOMEONE WOULD BE ASSIGNED TO GO VIEW THE SHIPMENT LATER ON. THE SHIPPER COULD NEVER BE CONTRACTED AS THE PHONE NUMBER THAT THEY HAD PROVIDED DID NOT WORK. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND THE CONSIGNEE LATER CAME AND PICKED THE SHIPMENT UP.

column168: IRISH VEHICLE WAS EXITING NOCO GAS STATION AND TURNING LEFT ONTO ROUTE 5. VEHICLE 2 WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED, PER WITNESSES STATEMENT AND STRUCK THE LEFT BACK CORNER OF THE IRISH VEHICLE CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN. THE IRISH VEHICLE HAS 3500 GALLONS OF PROPANE AND BECAUSE THE VEHICLE WAS ON IT’S SIDE THE LIQUID BEGUN TO COME OUT OF THE SAFETY RELEASE VALVE WHICH RESULTED IN THE HAZ MAT TEAM FLARING OFF LIQUID UNTIL THERE WAS NO LEAK. THE FLARING OFF TOOK EIGHT (8) HOURS.
column169: WE HAVE ANALYZED THIS ACCIDENT AND INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS TO AVOID LEFT TURNS WHENEVER POSSIBLE. IF THEY MUST MAKE ONE THEY WILL LOOK TWICE BOTH WAYS BEFORE TURNING.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0400 12/14/16 KCH TRACTOR 8011 PULLING TRAILER V500895 WITH LOAD NUMBER 0850127 WAS HEADING NORTH ON 124 AT MILE MARKER 85 JUST SOUTH OF RUTHERFORD TN. OUR VEHICLE WAS IN THE SLOW LANE BEHIND ANOTHER TRAC/TRAILER WHEN THE OTHER TRAC/TRAILER HITS A UNMARKED UTILITY TYPE TRAILER SITTING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE INTERSTATE. THE TRAC/TRAILER VEERED OFF TOT HE LEFT THROUGH THE MEDIAN RIGHT IN FRONT OF OUT TRAC/TRAILER AND JACK-KNIFED INTO 124 SOUTH. OUR DRIVER STATED THAT AFTER THE IMPACT IT FORCED HIM TO THE RIGHT AND HE WAS UNABLE TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE. HE WENT OFF THE INTERSTATE TO THE RIGHT AND DOWN AND EMBARKEMENT HITTING A TREE AND CAUSING AN EXPLOSION WHERE BOTH TRAC/TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE. HE WAS ABLE TO FREE HIMSELF AND WAS TAKEN TO NASHVILLE VIA AMBULANCE.     AT. APPROXIMATELY 0500 THE TN STATE PATROL CONTACTED BRANDON TRUCKER(KCH AFTER HOURS NUMBER) AND BRANDON IN TURN CALLED MIKE DAVIS(KCH SAFETY DIRECTOR). AT THAT POINT IN TIME MIKE CONTACTED KEN WHITAKER (KCH GM). WE WAITED TO HEAR BACK FROM TN STATE PATROL UNTIL 0630 TO NO AVAIL AT THAT TIME KEN AND MIKE WERE ABLE TO GET INTO THE OFFICE TO GATHER MORE DETAILS ON THE LOAD, ETC. KEN INFORMED AL WHITTEN AT 0640 AND JASON WHITTEN AT 0645. JASON, AL, KEN AND MIKE STARTED TRYING TO CONTACT HOSPITALS, LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND AMBULANCE SERVICES TO SEE WHERE OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO. WE WERE ABLE TO AL TALK TO OUR DRIVER AT 0715 AND HE CONFIRMED HE WAS IN THE HOSPITAL WITH SEVERAL DEGREE BURNS AND HAD A BROKEN FOOT FROM THE ACCIDENT. SURGERY ON HIS FOOT WAS TO BE PERFORMED AROUND 1100AM. HE WAS IN GOOD SPIRITS AND RE-ITERATED THE SERIES OF EVENTS ABOVE.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

OUR VEHICLE WAS IN THE SLOW LANE BEHIND ANOTHER TRAC/TRAILER WHEN THE OTHER TRAC/TRAILER HITS A UNMARKED UTILITY TYPE TRAILER SITTING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE INTERSTATE. THE TRAC/TRAILER VEERED OFF TOT HE LEFT THROUGH THE MEDIAN RIGHT IN FRONT OF OUT TRAC/TRAILER AND JACK-KNIFED INTO 124 SOUTH. OUR DRIVER STATED THAT AFTER THE IMPACT IT FORCED HIM TO THE RIGHT AND HE WAS UNABLE TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE. HE WENT OFF THE INTERSTATE TO THE RIGHT AND DOWN AND EMBARKEMENT HITTING A TREE AND CAUSING AN EXPLOSION WHERE BOTH TRAC/TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE. HE WAS ABLE TO FREE HIMSELF AND WAS TAKEN TO NASHVILLE VIA AMBULANCE.     AT. APPROXIMATELY 0500 THE TN STATE PATROL CONTACTED BRANDON TRUCKER(KCH AFTER HOURS NUMBER) AND BRANDON IN TURN CALLED MIKE DAVIS(KCH SAFETY DIRECTOR). AT THAT POINT IN TIME MIKE CONTACTED KEN WHITAKER (KCH GM). WE WAITED TO HEAR BACK FROM TN STATE PATROL UNTIL 0630 TO NO AVAIL AT THAT TIME KEN AND MIKE WERE ABLE TO GET INTO THE OFFICE TO GATHER MORE DETAILS ON THE LOAD, ETC. KEN INFORMED AL WHITTEN AT 0640 AND JASON WHITTEN AT 0645. JASON, AL, KEN AND MIKE STARTED TRYING TO CONTACT HOSPITALS, LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND AMBULANCE SERVICES TO SEE WHERE OUR DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO. WE WERE ABLE TO AL TALK TO OUR DRIVER AT 0715 AND HE CONFIRMED HE WAS IN THE HOSPITAL WITH SEVERAL DEGREE BURNS AND HAD A BROKEN FOOT FROM THE ACCIDENT. SURGERY ON HIS FOOT WAS TO BE PERFORMED AROUND 1100AM. HE WAS IN GOOD SPIRITS AND RE-ITERATED THE SERIES OF EVENTS ABOVE.

column168: DRIVER’S ORDERS WERE FOR DELIVERY OF DYED NO 2 DIESEL (HOME HEAT FUEL) TO RESIDENCE ADDRESS OF LANCASTER, OH AND MISTAKENLY MADE DELIVERY TO RESIDENCE AT LANCASTER, OH. AT 4:30 P.M. NOT REALIZING THE MISTAKEN ADDRESS, DRIVER DID FIND BASEMENT TANK FILL PIPE AND VENT PIPE LOCATED ON OUTSIDE FOUNDATION WALL OF HOUSE. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE DRIVER PRE-SET HIS METER FOR 540 GALLONS (AS DELIVERY ORDER NOTED CAPACITY OF 550 GALLONS AT THE 4600 CRUMLEY RD. LOCATION AND INITIATED OFF-LOADING OF THE NO. 2 DYED DIESEL INTO THE FILL PIPE AND INITIATED THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS INTO THE BASEMENT FUEL OIL TANK. DRIVER STATED IT WAS A COLD AND WINDY DAY, BUT THAT HE COULD FEEL AIR VENTING FROM THE VENT PIPE AND FELT DELIVERY WAS PROCEEDING PROPERLY. WHEN THE PRE-SET AMOUNT OF 540 GALLONS WAS DISPENSED THE PUMPING UNIT ON TRUCK SHUT DOWN AND AT THAT TIME DRIVER BECAME CONCERNED THAT HE MAY HAD A TANK OVERFILL AS THE PRE-SET AMOUNT OF 540 GALLONS WAS SO CLOSE TO THE NOTED 550 GALLON CAPACITY OF TANK(S) TO BE DELIVERED INTO. DRIVER THEN LAID HIS HOSE/NOZZLE ON GROUND AND ATTEMPTED TO LOOK INTO RESIDENCE BASEMENT WINDOWS TO SEE IF HE COULD OBSERVE ANYTHING THAT COULD LEND TOWARD A TANK OVERFILL OR ALIKE. DRIVER KNOCKED ON RESIDENCE DOORS AND WAS UNABLE TO GET RESPONSE FROM RESIDENTS. DRIVER CALLED INTO HIS CIRCLEVILLE. OH DISPATCH OFFICE AND SPOKE WITH LYKINS FACILITY MANAGER AND VOICED HIS CONCERNS. MANAGER RESPONDED TO SCENE AND WITH DRIVER AGAIN KNOCKED ON DOORS OF RESIDENCE WITH NO RESPONSE. MANAGER GOT ON-LINE VIA HIS SMART PHONE AND BY ADDRESS OF 4640 CRUMLEY ROAD WAS ABLE TO LOOK UP A PHONE NUMBER FOR RESIDENT AND THEN CALLED THE RESIDENT, WHO THEN DID ANSWER THE PHONE CALL AND UPON REQUEST CAME TO DOOR. MANAGER ASKED RESIDENT TO CHECK THEIR BASEMENT MAKE SURE IF THEIR BASEMENT TANK MAY HAVE BEEN OVERFILLED AND IF ANY FUEL HAD BEEN SPILLED. RESIDENT THEN ADVISED THERE WAS NO LONGER A TANK CONNECTED TO THE FILL PIPE, THAT WAS STILL IN-PLACE ON THE BACK WALL OF HOUSE, AS HE, THE RESIDENT, HAD PERSONALLY REMOVED THE FUEL TANK FROM BASEMENT A COUPLE OF YEARS PRIOR BUT HAD LEFT THE FILL AND VENT PIPES IN PLACE AND NOT DISABLE. RESIDENT CHECKED BASEMENT AND OBSERVED FUEL ON THE FLOOR AREA OF THE BASEMENT. RESIDENT ALLOWED OUR MANAGER AND DRIVER TO ENTER AND OBSERVE THE BASEMENT AREA AND IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT FUEL OIL WAS IN BASEMENT AREA OF HOUSE. MANAGER THEN PLACED CALL INTO LYKINS CORPORATE OFFICE AND ADVISED SAFETY DEPARTMENT OF THE SPILL INCIDENT. LYKINS SAFETY PERSONNEL THEN ADVISED MANAGER TO PLACE CALL TO 911 AND REPORT INCIDENT TO LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEN PLACED CALL TO OHEPA (SPILL INCIDENT REPORT ID 3 1612-23-2346//0); PLACED CALL AND SECURED SUPERIOR ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (SES) FOR INITIAL RESPONSE AND ALSO COORDINATED WITH LYKINS INSURANCE CARRIER TO SECURE SERVICES OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANT WITH SHIELD ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC.   LYKINS SAFETY DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO SITE WITH ARRIVAL AT 8:00 PM AND SES RESPONDED TO SITE ARRI
column169: ALL DRIVERS RECEIVE TRAINING IN PROPER PROCEDURAL PERFORMANCE OF ALL JOB FUNCTIONS, TO INCLUDE SUCH AS THE DELIVERY ASPECT ASSOCIATED TO HOME HEAT FUEL DELIVERIES INTO RESIDENTIAL FUEL OIL TANKS AS PER THIS INCIDENT. LYKINS TRANSPORTATION, INC. AS WELL HOLDS QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS WITH OPERATIONAL STAFF AND DRIVERS TO REVIEW VARIOUS AREAS SUCH AS MECHANICAL ISSUES, LOADING ISSUES, TRANSPORTATION ISSUES, DELIVERY ISSUES AND ALIKE AND HOW BEST PRACTICES CAN BE USED TO AVOID THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.  THE COMPANY REVIEWS ALL INCIDENTS TO DETERMINED CAUSATION AND ADDRESS IF THE INCIDENTS WERE PREVENTABLE OR NON-PREVENTABLE. IN THIS INSTANCE, IT WAS DETERMINED THE INCIDENT WAS PREVENTABLE AND COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED IF THE DRIVER HAD FOLLOWED PROPER JOB PERFORMANCE PROCEDURES. THE FAILURE TO VERIFY, BY THE DRIVER, THAT HE WAS NOT AT THE CORRECT ADDRESS AS NOTED ON OUR LYKINS PROVIDED LOAD TICKET IS PARAMOUNT IN THE CAUSATION OF THIS INCIDENT. THE DRIVER ALSO FAILED TO ADHERE TO PROPER DELIVERY PROCEDURES FOR A BASEMENT HOME HEAT FUEL OIL TANK; THAT THOUGH MAY NOT HAVE PREVENTED THE INCIDENT, WOULD HAVE GREATLY MINIMIZED THE AMOUNT OF FUEL THAT WAS DELIVERED AND ENTERED INTO THE BASEMENT, AS WELL AS NEAR THE FILL PIPE OF THE RESIDENCE HAD HE DONE SO.   DRIVERS WILL BE BRIEFED ON THE OCCURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT AND THE CAUSATION FACTORS ASSOCIATED TO THE INCIDENT AS WELL AS A REVIEW OF PROPER BEST-PRACTICE DELIVERY PROCEDURES AT THE QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS AND AS PART OF OUR ON-GOING TRAINING PROGRAMS.
